    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly, let's strip away the goblin metaphors and get straight to the point. In the context of the indemnification clause you've mentioned, it means that you, as the Consultant, agree to cover the Client and its associates for any claims, liabilities, damages, losses, costs, and expenses that arise from your performance of the services or any breach of the agreement. This can indeed become an unlimited risk for you, as it could potentially require you to cover all costs and damages, no matter the size.\n\nTo limit this liability, you should indeed look for a cap on the damages or a more specific limitation of liability clause. This would set a maximum amount you're responsible for, which can help protect you from unlimited financial exposure. It's also wise to negotiate terms that clearly define what constitutes a breach and under what circumstances you're required to indemnify the Client. Consulting with a legal professional can help you understand these clauses better and negotiate terms that are more favorable to you.",
